ews turned practically all of American culture—from blackface minstrel shows to the works of William Shakespeare—into a battlefield in the war on insanity. Reiss also shows how asylums touched the lives and shaped the writing of key figures, such as Emerson and Poe, who viewed the system alternately as the fulfillment of a democratic ideal and as a kind of medical enslavement. Without neglecting this troubling contradiction, Theaters of Madness prompts us to reflect on what our society can learn from a generation that urgently and creatively tried to solve the problem of mental illness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aHospitals in literaturexHistoryx19th century. 0aHospitals in literaturexHistoryy19th century. 0aMentally ill, Writings of the, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aPsychiatric hospitalsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPsychiatric hospitalsxSocial aspectsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aPsychiatric hospitalsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPsychiatric hospitalszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226709659423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226709659.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles